            "Item1": "[EMAIL - 25##-12-07-11-23-10-6017]\n<>\nSUBJECT: Congratulations!!\nFROM: <corrupt:0xFF0BEA>\nTO: GROUP <corrupt:0xFC0002>\n<>\n[CONTENTS]\n\nDear scientists,\n\nThe creation of a gonosimulistic (use the term correctly) mammal capable of asexual reproduction is an astonishing breakthrough of science. This has never been seen before in nature. Not sure we can call them mammals anymore... It proves to me and to <corrupt:0x0001FC> that there is nothing this team cannot do.\n\nI wish to thank everybody who contributed to this amazing feat. It greatly reduces the cost and complexity of their production, as it is not necessary to create and organize separate male and female Sawians. The lack of sex drive also curbs overpopulation and avoids any incidents while still allowing them to reproduce.\n<>\nYou can expect a reward from me soon.\n\nYours in good faith,\n<corrupt:0xFF0BEA>\n<>\n[ATTACHMENTS]\n\nREF: [INTERNAL MEMORANDUM - 25##-12-07-09-12-40-0157]\n\nENTITY CLASS: Biological\nENTITY SUBCLASS: Sawian\n<>\n[CONTENTS]\n\nThis memorandum establishes mandatory terminology policy regarding the Sawian species and supersedes all prior documentation, annotations, and informal usage.\n\nEffective immediately, the term \"hermaphrodite\" is **banned in all corporate communications**, including scientific, operational, cultural, and casual contexts. The sole exception is explicit historical reference (e.g., quotations, legacy documentation analysis, or discussion of obsolete Earth taxonomies), which must be clearly labeled as such.\n\nThe approved descriptor for Sawian reproductive biology is \"gonosimulistic.\"  \nContext-dependent alternatives include \"cosexual\" and \"monoecious.\"\n\nUse of the term outside of these narrow historical contexts is considered inappropriate, reductive, and professionally suspect. This introduces avoidable interpretive risk and will be reviewed under the Stakeholder-Facing Language Control Framework.\n<>\nNo human naturally